<div align="left">
		
		<hr align="left" width="100%" />
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_40229">Uh oh, time to get all theoretical on your azz.  <br />
<br />
People play games like D&amp;D to primarily, yes, build power for themselves. But note, it's about building power, not getting it. For a character to walk into a new game with an old, stacked character, what does that do to the rest of the party? Think, the lvl 9 thief reminisces about that time he fell into the pit trap of sleeping black widows, and almost blew his MS/HIS roll trying to sneak out. But he did find his +3/type-e poison short sword down there! Or the level 10 Paladin, who remembers volunteering to be geased so the temple would ressurect a fallen comrade. Little did he know it would end up in him becoming a semi-avatar of his god, including his ultra-special deific armor and weapons! <br />
<br />
Building power is supposed to give players something to remember, it gives their character's history, personality, and it creates a sense value in the levels they have and the equipment they get. What is worth more to you? Getting a +3 Longsword of the body of an ogre you guys killed(among the 8 total you encountered), or getting that +3 longsword after exploring the depths of the catacombs, slaying the guardian, and solving the puzzle? Dumping a character into the world that has stuff and powers you didn't give him leaves him only with the memorys and appreciation for his stuff that he got in someone else's game, under someone else's ideas.<br />
<br />
Maybe that doesn't strike you as bad, but again, consider this. That paladin that has been in your world for a year and a half, he is used to policing himself and his actions because he status and position rely on his good or "in-character" behavior. So he won't be threatening NPCs to make the plot move using his powers, he won't bash down the walls of the legal merchant to see the map he has hidden in the shop, he won't just slaughter NPCs out of character and on a whim, he has things to lose and he knows how they will be lost.<br />
<br />
The flip side, an example from RL. Back in the day, we all used to make PCs based on video game heros. Well, one player had Ryu, the monk. And he wanted to bring him to an admittedly, more mature and developed campaign. ALL other eastern classes in that game were very, very cautious when thinking about their actions, their impact on their status with their sensei, and their dojos, clans, associations, was at the forefront of their self-policing. The monk comes in, gets a level or two, loses 3/4 of his magic items, gets assigned a dojo and a master, blah blah blah. The first game we play, we are talking to a noble daiymo, and the monk tries to @#%$ strong arm him, right there! When the guards come, and we are all explaining to him that his sensei will disown him, he will be a fugitive in the land, ect... And he just shrugs, because his character has no value to him, he hasn't worked for what he has gotten, it's about the numbers on paper not the being in his imagination. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I totally don' disagree that the game is about acquiring power. But with great power [insert cliche' line here]. Giving power to players must always be balanced against risk to the players, and responsibilities. Give a player an aritifact with great power and no strings attached, and the first thing that player will do is abuse it as much as they can imagine, forcing you to put the smack down on them. Even though someone is transfering over a character in this case, it's from a different game. That player is essentially being given a new character, with a big shiny artifact, and no restraints or cost. <br />
<br />
It's like gambling. When you've won $2000 after losing $400 dollars to get there, you eye your money and weigh the risks of gambling it. If you walk into the casino, and someone just gives you $2000, you go buck nutty! It's not "your" money in the sense you had no risk in it, so you behave differently with it. <br />
<br />
 </div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
	<br>
