		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_40230">Quote:And he just shrugs, because his character has no value to him, he hasn't worked for what he has gotten, it's about the numbers on paper not the being in his imagination. Forgive me, but that's not a consequence of his starting character level, it's a starting consequence of someone not caring about the game.  There was a player in my last group who behaved this way ALL THE TIME, even when playing a character he'd been playing for months.<br />
<br />
Quote:Give a player an aritifact with great power and no strings attached, and the first thing that player will do is abuse it as much as they can imagine, forcing you to put the smack down on them. Well, ideally, the world should punish your players for their actions, not you as the DM - if the players do something unconscionable, have the local justice system try to punish them for it - if the players stomp all over the posse sent to capture them, the magistrate can hire a hero from another town.  If the players defeat the hero, other heroes will get wind of things, and the players will have to face more and more powerful adversaries that pursue them.  And, if they defeat everything they face - well, that sounds like a pretty awesome campaign to me.<br />
<br />
 </div>
