<div align="left">
		
		<hr align="left" width="100%" />
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_40234">No, you didn't say a word of that - but the metaphor you chose most definitely gave that impression.<br />
<br />
Quote:If it's part of the story, they can damn well do what they please. If they are ruining the story, for everyone else, and for me, it's bad gaming.See, this is what I don't understand - trying to confine PC behavior to a pre-set &quot;story&quot; seems like extreme metagaming to me.  In most of the best games I've played, the DM gives you a hook, and you can either go with it, or pursue your group's own goals - the DM either scraps the storyline he had set up or saves it for a later time, and improvises a new one.  This reinforces the idea that the PCs are in a living world, wherein they are in control of where they go and what they do, with the DM controlling only the world, not the game.  That is what I meant when I said, 'The world should punish the players, not the DM'.  <br />
<br />
Quote:And I prep to have my bases covered against PCs going over the top or running wild. Again, I fail to understand why either of these is a bad thing.  Doesn't your world have characters that go over the top and run wild that are NPCs?  And, usually, aren't these villains?<br />
<br />
This is the difference between a scenario and a game world - in a scenario, bad guys sit in their rooms and wait for the PCs to come and defeat them.  In a game world, events transpire however they would have transpired normally, save for the disruption of events by the PCs (which is the whole point of the PCs' game experience).  Our DM actually encouraged us to do whatever we wanted, whether it was running amok, slaughtering his favorite NPCs, destroying whole towns, whatever we wanted - but he always made sure there were consequences to ANYTHING we did, good or bad, so that we would regulate our behavior based upon not whether or not we were doing what he wanted us to, but rather upon what we were doing was (a) in character and (b) sensible.   -- Marauder Arafain Entreri, 65 Deceiver<br />
  -- Arafein Soulstriker, 54 Champion Relic (deceased)<br />
  -- Arafax Kokorozan, 20 Monk Giantfriend (missing)<br />
  -- Formerly of Requiem of Souls and Crusaders of Plilo<br />
  -- Formerly of The Rathe Server, now of Zebuxoruk<br />
  -- My ghetto gear<br />
&quot;Once, in the old west, a gentleman shot a professional gunfighter in the back. When asked why he didn't give the other chap a chance to draw, he replied, 'Well, he's dead and I'm alive and that's how I wanted it to be.&quot; -- from Red Planet, Robert A. Heinlein<br />
<br />
</div>
