		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_40237">Example(a real one): PCs walk up to this door in the side of the mountain. All of them were drawn there by mysterious circumstances. The door is made of black metal, and has corrosion marks all over it, black bubbles made of corroded metal, the door breathes in and out like it is alive. The PCs are gathered, trying to decide how best to approach it, when one PC(a player who is impatient and hates to communicate) runs up and smashes the door with his hammer, ignoring the cries of the PCs(and the shouts of the people at the table). End result: 2 PCs dead, 2 more almost fatally injured.<br />
<br />
<br />
Another good one: PCs are in a town, trying to get permission to borrow a holy relic from the church in order to do something. The entire town is peace bonded(weapons are bound with wire and drawing them is a serious, jailable offense). Negotiations are not going well. One of the players, who hasn't been involved in any of the negotiations/interactions, decides he's going to go walk around town(he's playing a bi-polar banished elven prince who is more than slightly unbalanced). While walking around, he decides he's going to teach a boy he meets how to sword fight! Using his peace bound sword, he starts instructing the kid where the kill points are ect....Then a guard comes up. The PC takes the bound sword, and starts motioning the guard's neck and crotch with it. The guard gets angry, tells him to desist or he's going to jail. All he had to do was put the sword down, and walk away. The PC ignores him completely, goes to jail, instead. <br />
<br />
The next two hours involved one PC trying to create a legal defense for the other at his court appearance, and the wizard breaking into the temple of the most powerful deity in the world to rescue the captured PC, making us all criminals, forcing us all to flee, almost making us kill innocent guards. To rectify the situation, we had to strong arm the dm into letting us kill the offending party members, present them to the court as proof of their punishment, then resurrecting them so we could continue on.<br />
<br />
A whole night of adventuring, fux0rd, because one player decided to 'do his own thing', forcing a reaction out of the world, while me and 2 other players who had no intentions on being fugitives or law breakers, sat there bored for the whole night while all this insanity went on.  <br />
<br />
<br />
That is about as good an example of desructive gaming I can think of. If our whole party had been behind the jail break, it would have been an adventure. Instead, it turned into 2 PCs who like to make trouble into center stage attractions for the whole night, while the rest of us LG, LN players just sat there going "PUT THE @#%$ SWORD DOWN SO WE CAN GET ON WITH THIS". </div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
	<br>
