<div align="left">
		
		<hr align="left" width="100%" />
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_40241">My group is an odd mix. I've got one rock solid player who loves to play a concept, likes to think about plot lines, likes to talk to his party. I have one gamer who has been my buddy since the days of Ninja Gaiden and Final Fantasy who admittedly, likes to play because he likes power, likes killing stuff, likes rolling dice. Most of the other players fall in the middle of those two(their brothers, actually  ). I can appreciate both of their play styles, but it puts me under a lot of stress as a DM #1 to keep everyone intrested in their own way and #2 deal with the various ways in which they are going to try and solve a situation. The former PC likes to explore, understand, within his character concept. The latter, prefers to meta-game somewhat, get some information, and make a decision based on his gut(not his characters) which is uselessly, go kick the bad guy's ass. <br />
<br />
In an intresting plot line, they all usually are on the same page. But when someone gets bored, or a unique situation presents itself(the lord of the castle has been wounded in a practice duel, and he doesn't want you to heal him! Quick, web the corridor so he can't escape! NO! Call his guards to restrain him because he is beside himself! NO! Let him go, he's Lord of his bloody castle! NO! Everyone fall back and let me tail him to see what he's doing! NO! He's a vampyre, that's why he doesn't want standard clerical healing, kill him!!!!!), the disparities in play styles becomes very apparent. <br />
<br />
For me as a DM, I have to think very carefully about how I lay out situations with my PCs, because there is honestly never any telling how the party as a whole is going to take it, or how an individual PC is going to try to deal with. What makes matters worse is(and is my biggest player pet peeve) that most of my PCs are the "say it in character first then talk about it with the players later". Table talk about the plot is something I encourage. It may not be realistic for the characters themselves to talk about it together, but that shouldnt' stop PCs from using their brains. And if they talk about it, and people still act on purely character motivations, well, then the party and I have done all that can be done, and if it goes south, it goes south. It's the abscence of that chance to talk things over that concern the whole party that really pisses me off. <br />
<br />
So if I come off a little........heavy handed with my games, it's because it's been my experience that a session can be moving along nicely one minute, and collapse into players pissed off at each other and the situation, in the space of getting up to get a Mtn. Dew.  </div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
