<div align="left">
		
		<hr align="left" width="100%" />
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_40244">&quot;It sounds to me that you game with ***********&quot;<br />
<br />
/agree<br />
<br />
My favorite tactic for reigning in people who actively FSU is to get everyone on the same page as far as playing their character in character. If someone acts like a psycho upstart who's always in trouble with the law, chars shouldn't have to bail them out unless they actually want to. (And L-anything chars may not enjoy adventuring with them at all.) They'll either learn that they can't just ignore the party's wishes and expect to always be bailed out during play, or they'll learn it in jail while the party goes on to actually adventure. Saving that kind of person's butt all the time only teaches them they can behave like a tool and never worry about it.*<br />
<br />
One of my favorite &quot;people actually play in character?!&quot; moments: The party was going.. somewhere. A river was in the way. On the shore, an old man was sleeping in a fishing boat. When the party woke him up, he was belligerent and refused to let them borrow his boat. Instead of either trying to haggle or just moving on to try to find another way, one of the players started trying to just take the boat. The old man fought him as effectively as a feeb can fight, and the player responded in the manner of an experienced rollplayer - lethal force. Instead of sighing with relief and getting in the boat, or simply complaining, the very Good oriented party subdued him, turned him in to the city watch for murder, and then continued on the adventure.  </div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
	<br>
<br>
